  <title translate="true">Tip #44</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Heading3"><text styleclass="Heading3" translate="true">Tip of the Day</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table rowcount="1" colcount="2" style="cell-padding:0px; cell-spacing:0px; border-width:0px; cell-border-width:0px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td style="width:58px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><image src="TipOfTheDayBulb.jpg" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption"></image></para>
        </td>
        <td style="width:328px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Don&apos;t know how to write a particular method? Simply create a stub method containing a </text><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">self halt</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> expression and cause the method to be invoked. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Once in the </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Debugger</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> you will find that the extra context of call stack, arguments, instance variables, etc, somehow makes the problem seem much more concrete and easier to solve. </text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">You will also find that the auto-completion facilities are even more helpful when programming inside the debugger in this way. This is due to the additional type information that is available during the execution of a method.</text><snippet src="Tip_Of_The_Day_Footer"/></para>
  </body>
